A horizontal shear with factor $s_{h}$ maps $(x,y)$ to $(x+s_{h}y, y)$. As a matrix acting on column vectors, this is
$$
H=\begin{pmatrix}
1 & s_{h} \\
0 & 1
\end{pmatrix}
=\begin{pmatrix}
1 & \frac{3}{2} \\
0 & 1
\end{pmatrix}.
$$
A vertical shear with factor $s_{v}$ maps $(x,y)$ to $(x, y+s_{v}x)$. As a matrix, this is
$$
V=\begin{pmatrix}
1 & 0 \\
s_{v} & 1
\end{pmatrix}
=\begin{pmatrix}
1 & 0 \\
-\frac{1}{2} & 1
\end{pmatrix}.
$$
Applying the horizontal shear first and then the vertical shear corresponds to the combined linear transformation $T=VH$. Compute
$$
T=VH=\begin{pmatrix}
1 & 0 \\
-\frac{1}{2} & 1
\end{pmatrix}
\begin{pmatrix}
1 & \frac{3}{2} \\
0 & 1
\end{pmatrix}
=\begin{pmatrix}
1\cdot 1+0\cdot 0 & 1\cdot \frac{3}{2}+0\cdot 1 \\
-\frac{1}{2}\cdot 1+1\cdot 0 & -\frac{1}{2}\cdot \frac{3}{2}+1\cdot 1
\end{pmatrix}
=\begin{pmatrix}
1 & \frac{3}{2} \\
-\frac{1}{2} & \frac{1}{4}
\end{pmatrix}.
$$
Thus, for any point $(x,y)$, the transformed coordinates are
$$
\begin{pmatrix}
x' \\
y'
\end{pmatrix}
=T\begin{pmatrix}
x \\
y
\end{pmatrix}
=\begin{pmatrix}
x+\frac{3}{2}y \\
-\frac{1}{2}x+\frac{1}{4}y
\end{pmatrix}.
$$
Applying $T$ to the given vertices (as columns):
- $A=(0,0)$ gives $A'=(0,0)$.
- $B=(1,0)$ gives $B'=\left(1,-\frac{1}{2}\right)$.
- $C=(1,1)$ gives $C'=\left(\frac{5}{2},-\frac{1}{4}\right)$.
- $D=(0,1)$ gives $D'=\left(\frac{3}{2},\frac{1}{4}\right)$.

Therefore, the $2\times 4$ matrix with columns $A'$, $B'$, $C'$, $D'$ is
$$
\begin{pmatrix}
0 & 1 & \frac{5}{2} & \frac{3}{2} \\
0 & -\frac{1}{2} & -\frac{1}{4} & \frac{1}{4}
\end{pmatrix}.
$$
